{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8a0e155e-72a7-4a09-ab86-b1fdddb2ec06","content":"Here's how to configure `.vscode/mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using stdio transport:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Place this file at `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root.\n- `\"type\": \"stdio\"` means VS Code communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your MCP server must read JSON-RPC requests from stdin and write responses to stdout (avoid writing anything else to stdout — use stderr for logs).\n\nIf you've already published or built the project, you can point to the DLL directly:\n\n```json\n\"command\": \"dotnet\",\n\"args\": [\"path/to/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n```\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot chat in agent mode and your server's tools should appear automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bfde586a-623f-4972-9603-e3e3a0ceb605","outputTokens":258,"requestId":"2C02:2B537A:2970976:2DCD32F:69FD363F"},"id":"7c925581-5417-44ef-897f-cdd49fa48316","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:03:02.591Z","parentId":"5c5a9250-4e8a-40ff-bef7-fb2432ee31f9"}
